Predicting recall RT with 2AFC RT (v2.0)

Mar 3, 2021

Exclusions

  • Excluding 0 participants who gave incorrect resonses on fewer than 25% of recall trials, leaving 30 participants in the analysis.
  • Dropping 29 recall trials with reaction times over more than 3 sds above the mean (more than 5.6 seconds), leaving 541 trials in the analysis.

AFC RT -> Recall RT

We want to see if the reaction time on 2AFC trials for a given word are predictive of reaction time for the same word in the recall task.

Est. S.E. t val. p
(Intercept) 5.878 0.270 21.766 0.000
log_afc_rt 0.212 0.038 5.550 0.000
Standard errors: OLS

This looks promising, but it could be driven by individual differences. We need to see the effect within individuals.

Fixed Effects
Est. S.E. t val. d.f. p
(Intercept) 6.457 0.356 18.139 448.779 0.000
log_afc_rt 0.133 0.050 2.655 470.040 0.008
p values calculated using Satterthwaite d.f.

Looks like we still see a positive relationship. We can visualize it more clearly by applying participant-wise mean centering:

And here is the distribution of slopes (with 95% confidence intervals).

67% of participants have a positive slope. This is a good sign, but it’s still not great. The estimates are super noisy so it’s hard to know how much of this is real. Here’s a similar plot with the correlation.

AFC accuracy

This looks promising, but it turns out this one is driven entirely by individual differences (each line is a participant). Mixed effects regression shows no effect of 2AFC trials, especially when we account for RT on the correct 2AFC trials.

The slope appears to be constant over rounds.

But the correlation is higher in rounds 2 and 3. (Look at the last column in the correlation matrix)
